{"id":14881414,"mediaExerciseId":"819e7bd7-3b96-44b1-8e94-5783cc11144e","exerciseName":"15","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612376,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":453,"solutions":[{"id":5997334,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to determine the expected return on the market using CAPM. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/e8f3170e284ff5f907a722747bf2e19d/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/e8f3170e284ff5f907a722747bf2e19d/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **capital asset pricing model (CAPM)** is an equation that shows how systematic risk and expected returns are related. The CAPM informs us that the expected return is influenced by the time value of money, theÂ risk premium, and the stock's beta compared to an average value.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/d12d49f80e9ead926fb4def6cbe78f09/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/d12d49f80e9ead926fb4def6cbe78f09/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let's first identify the given amounts in the problem: \n\n\n| | Amount$\\hspace{5pt}$| \n|:--|--:| \n|Expected return | 10.45\\%|\n|Beta| 0.93|\n|Risk-free rate | 3.6\\%|","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":99,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/1a4ebc3b94e085daf651162ea5b7a742/lateximg_large.png","width":1009},"regular":{"height":51,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/1a4ebc3b94e085daf651162ea5b7a742/lateximg.png","width":506}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{r }_{I}&={\\text{R}_{f}} + {{[B}_{I}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(R}_{m}} - {\\text{R}_{f}}{)]}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nWhere: \n$$\\begin{aligned}\n{\\text{r}_{I}}& = {\\text{Cost of capital for an investment}} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{f}}& = {\\text{Risk-free interest rate }} \\\\\n{\\text{R}_{m}}& = {\\text{Market expected return  }} \\\\\n{\\text{B}_{I}} &= {\\text{Beta}} \n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":326,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/eff1f4a1215161604deedc63598f29fc/lateximg_large.png","width":759},"regular":{"height":164,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/eff1f4a1215161604deedc63598f29fc/lateximg.png","width":378}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"First, let us insert the provided data to the formula from step 4. As an illustration, here's what it looks like: \n\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{10.45\\%}&={\\text{3.6\\%}} + {{[0.93}}{\\text{ $\\times$ }}{\\text{(R}_{m}} - {\\text{3.6\\%}}{)]}\\\\\n\\text{10.45\\%}&={\\text{3.6\\%}} +{{0.93}}{\\text{R}_{m}} - {\\text{3.35\\%}}{}\\\\\n\\text{10.45\\%}&={{0.93}}{\\text{R}_{m}} + {\\text{0.25\\%}}{}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":223,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/8595d8397f56bc4cc021531fd740f68c/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":113,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/8595d8397f56bc4cc021531fd740f68c/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, let us rearrange the formual by shifting the 0.93 to the other side. This is done as follows: \n\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n{{- 0.93}}{\\text{R}_{m}}&={\\text{0.25\\%}}\\text{- 10.45\\%}\\\\\n{{- 0.93}}{\\text{R}_{m}}&= {\\text{-10.20\\%}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":177,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/e17f0ef83c09867e76c0598abf464c4c/lateximg_large.png","width":993},"regular":{"height":90,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/e17f0ef83c09867e76c0598abf464c4c/lateximg.png","width":496}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6},{"columns":[{"text":"Then, let us divide both sides by -0.93\\%. This is to cancel out the coefficient of Rm. This is computed as follows: \n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\n{{- 0.93}}{\\text{R}_{m}}&=- {\\text{10.20\\%}}\\\\\n\\dfrac{{- 0.93}{\\text{R}_{m}}}{\\text{ -0.93}}&=\\dfrac{\\text{-10.20\\%}}{\\text{-0.93 }}\\\\\n{\\text{R}_{m}}&={\\textbf{10.97\\%}}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":7},{"columns":[{"text":"**To conclude, the expected return on the market is 10.97\\%.**","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":30,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/08e077b2fc3556f9dc6e6094bbe3e5a8/lateximg_large.png","width":837},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/09/f005e539055c3231bb40183e7c198251/08e077b2fc3556f9dc6e6094bbe3e5a8/lateximg.png","width":420}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":8}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"5885d7a2-7990-4e7d-9c7d-ff08a0896632","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":8}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881415,"exerciseName":"16","page":453,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"24d0ba6e-5632-4747-ab6c-6cd08ffb39c4","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-16-24d0ba6e-5632-4747-ab6c-6cd08ffb39c4"},{"id":14881416,"exerciseName":"17","page":453,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"fe4defbc-801a-4e0a-8bfe-3f0fa74fe0cb","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-17-fe4defbc-801a-4e0a-8bfe-3f0fa74fe0cb"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881413,"exerciseName":"14","page":453,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"256d3243-c6d0-4856-8f99-ec57aa5b3bc4","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-13-questions-and-problems-14-256d3243-c6d0-4856-8f99-ec57aa5b3bc4"},{"id":14881412,"exerciseName":"13","page":453,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"0f574367-d4b5-4887-b238-b41645e93fa4","_we